EMP Impact on Telecommunications
To aid in understanding the impact of EMP on telecommunications, figure 3-1 provides
a simplified diagram of a telecommunications network.
Service subscribers communicate through a local node. For example, a cellular subscriber
communicates through a cell tower controlled by a cellular base station. If communication
is with a party located on another local node, the communications traffic may
be routed through the backbone to the distant local node for delivery to the other party.
The backbone connects to thousands of local nodes and in doing so serves a transport and
routing function to move voice, data, or video traffic between or among the communicators.
It consists of a mix of equipment that provides high-speed connectivity between the
local nodes. In an actual network if there is sufficient traffic between two local nodes,
they may be directly connected by transmission media such as fiber links. Figure 3-1
